I introduced a bill with @SenJohnBarrasso and @SenatorRomney to help ensure accuracy with community college graduation rate reporting by more appropriately reflecting the diversity of more part-time, non-first-time students. https://www.enzi.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/news-releases?ID=1E23490D-7E37-434E-847F-987020E4E717 …
It’s important for students and families to have the most accurate information before choosing a college that best fits their needs.
This NDAA has a much different budgetary impact than the bill the Senate reported earlier this year. Congress has the power to change course and I hope we do in the future.

For example, it includes a non-defense provision that will provide all federal employees with 12 weeks of paid parental leave. This is a new benefit that costs more than $8 billion, and it passed without debate by inclusion in this defense bill.

Our nation is on an unsustainable fiscal course. We simply cannot continue down this path. While the NDAA is well-intentioned with many proposals I support, it ignores our overspending problem & furthers the practice of passing legislation while ignoring the rules of the Senate. pic.twitter.com/jokYrqOo02

I introduced legislation today with @SenatorJonTester that would cement into law how government agencies regulate food produced using animal cell-culture technology so folks know what they are eating and that it is safe. https://www.enzi.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/news-releases?ID=F267A4BB-7B01-492A-A84C-2B2B4D9F2A8C …
Emerging cell-culture technologies may reshape the food industry in the coming years. Existing food safety laws were drafted long before these technologies were contemplated.

It is time to end unnecessary shutdowns for good. https://www.enzi.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/2019/12/enzi-supports-bipartisan-plan-to-end-government-shutdowns …

Wyoming is also home to the first woman governor, first woman justice of the peace, first all-woman jury and many more accomplishments. My wife Diana joins me in commemorating our state for these monumental milestones.

We are celebrating an incredible landmark today – 150 years ago, Wyoming led the way by granting women the right to vote and hold office. The Equality State is proud to have taken this important step 50 years before the enactment of the 19th Amendment. pic.twitter.com/q2ohLvhEk5

150 years ago, on Dec. 10, 1869, the Wyoming Territory approved the first law in the history of the United States recognizing women’s inherent right to vote and to hold public office. Learn more: https://bit.ly/2E2WsaE

Tomorrow is Wyoming Women's Suffrage Day, a testament to the contributions women have made – and continue to make – to Wyoming and the values that make our state stand out as an example for the rest of the country. pic.twitter.com/AvTNcXZp26
